---

<BaseLayout
  title="Med-Surgical 28 — Cynthia Bennet"
  description="Unfolding case study: UTI and Anaphylactic Reaction Secondary to Medication Error (MED-28)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/med-surgical/`}>Med-Surgical</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Med-Surgical 28 — Cynthia Bennet</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Allergy / Medication Safety</span>
    <h1>Med-Surgical 28 — Cynthia Bennet</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">UTI and Anaphylactic Reaction Secondary to Medication Error</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Cynthia Bennet, 34 years, African American</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">It is Monday 1300. You are the nurse receiving Cynthia Bennet back from hemodialysis. You review the handoff and prepare to assess the patient at the bedside.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Cynthia Bennet</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>34 years · African American</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Urinary tract infection (UTI); fever of unknown origin → UTI diagnosed</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Medical History</th><td>Type 1 diabetes mellitus (T1DM), End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD), Hemodialysis</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>⚠️ <strong>PENICILLIN</strong> — documented on allergy band</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admitted</th><td>Monday AM from ED for fever of unknown origin → UTI confirmed</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Current Status</th><td>Returning from hemodialysis at 1300</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🚨 Scene: What You Find at the Bedside</h3>
        <div class="callout callout-danger">
          <strong>⚠️ MEDICATION ERROR IDENTIFIED</strong>
          <p>Cynthia returns from dialysis with an IV infusing. You perform your SWIPE check — the <strong>allergy band shows PENICILLIN allergy</strong>. You cross-reference the IV bag: <strong>Ampicillin IV</strong>. The dialysis nurse started the first dose of ampicillin.</p>
          <p><strong>Ampicillin is a penicillin-class antibiotic.</strong> This patient has a documented penicillin allergy. This is a <strong>preventable medication error</strong>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you recognize the error? Why is ampicillin dangerous for this patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Cross-reference: Ampicillin → Penicillin class:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Ampicillin is an aminopenicillin — a subclass of penicillin antibiotics</li>
          <li>Patients with penicillin allergy have IgE antibodies against penicillin antigens that are structurally shared across penicillin-class drugs</li>
          <li>Administering ampicillin to a penicillin-allergic patient is a predictable trigger for an allergic reaction, potentially anaphylaxis</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Allergy check before every medication:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Verify the patient's allergy band at every medication administration — not just at admission</li>
          <li>Cross-reference drug class, not just drug name</li>
          <li>The dialysis unit team did not check allergies before starting the IV — this is the root cause of the impending emergency</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Immediate action:</strong> Do not wait for symptoms — stop the ampicillin infusion and notify the provider immediately.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Within minutes of arrival, Cynthia begins reporting new symptoms…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Anaphylaxis Development</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Before you can stop the infusion, Cynthia reports feeling itchy. Symptoms escalate rapidly. Vital signs begin to deteriorate.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📉 Deteriorating Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Direction</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Blood Pressure</td><td class="text-danger">↓ Falling</td><td>Vasodilation → distributive shock</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Heart Rate</td><td class="text-danger">↑ Rising</td><td>Compensatory tachycardia</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SpO₂</td><td class="text-danger">↓ Dropping</td><td>Bronchoconstriction → hypoxemia</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Respiratory Rate</td><td class="text-danger">↑ Increasing</td><td>Airway compromise → tachypnea</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩺 Anaphylaxis by Body System</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>System</th><th>Symptoms</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Dermatological</strong></td><td>Pruritus (itching) — <em>first symptom</em>, urticaria (hives), erythema, angioedema</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Respiratory</strong></td><td>Wheezing, stridor, dyspnea, laryngeal edema, cyanosis</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Cardiovascular</strong></td><td>Hypotension, tachycardia, thready pulse, cardiac arrest (severe)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>GI</strong></td><td>Nausea, vomiting, crampy abdominal pain, diarrhea</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>⏱ Symptom Progression Timeline</h3>
      <div class="chain-flow">
        <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem"><span class="chain-icon">🔴</span><strong>Pruritus (generalized itching)</strong><small>First symptom — IgE-mast cell activation beginning</small></div>
        <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem"><span class="chain-icon">🔴</span><strong>Urticaria (hives)</strong><small>Histamine released → increased vascular permeability</small></div>
        <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem"><span class="chain-icon">🔴</span><strong>Wheezing</strong><small>Bronchoconstriction — airway compromise</small></div>
        <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="chain-step chain-step-consequence"><span class="chain-icon">🚨</span><strong>Hypotension + tachycardia + SpO₂ drop</strong><small>Full anaphylactic shock — LIFE-THREATENING</small></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pathophysiology: Type I IgE-Mediated Hypersensitivity — How Anaphylaxis Occurs</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Mechanism of anaphylaxis (Type I hypersensitivity):</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sensitization:</strong> Previous exposure to penicillin triggered production of IgE antibodies; these are bound to mast cells and basophils throughout the body</li>
          <li><strong>Re-exposure:</strong> Ampicillin enters the bloodstream → binds to IgE antibodies on mast cells</li>
          <li><strong>Degranulation:</strong> Mast cells and basophils rapidly release inflammatory mediators: histamine, tryptase, prostaglandins, leukotrienes</li>
          <li><strong>Systemic effects:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Histamine → vasodilation → hypotension; increased vascular permeability → third-spacing</li>
              <li>Leukotrienes → bronchoconstriction → wheezing, dyspnea</li>
              <li>Bradykinin → angioedema → airway compromise</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>This is a <strong>Type I IgE-mediated</strong> hypersensitivity reaction — the fastest and most dangerous type. Onset within seconds to minutes of exposure.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Emergency response must begin immediately — every second counts…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Emergency Response — Stop and Treat</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Cynthia is wheezing, hypotensive, and tachycardic. You must act in rapid sequence. This is a life-threatening emergency.</p>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚨 Immediate Anaphylaxis Response — In Order</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>1</strong></td><td><strong>STOP the ampicillin</strong> — clamp the IV tubing. Do NOT disconnect or remove the IV catheter.</td><td>Remove the allergen; keep venous access for emergency medications</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>2</strong></td><td>Change to new IV tubing; flush with 0.9% Normal Saline</td><td>Clears residual ampicillin from tubing before new medications infuse</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>3</strong></td><td><strong>CALL FOR HELP</strong> — activate rapid response or emergency team</td><td>Anaphylaxis requires team response; do not manage alone</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>4</strong></td><td><strong>Epinephrine 1:1000 — 0.3 mg IM into the lateral thigh</strong></td><td>FIRST-LINE drug — fastest absorption via lateral thigh; not SQ</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>5</strong></td><td>Apply oxygen via <strong>non-rebreather mask (NRB)</strong></td><td>High-flow O₂ (10–15 L/min) for hypoxemia/bronchoconstriction</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>6</strong></td><td>Lay patient flat; elevate legs if hypotensive</td><td>Increases venous return → supports blood pressure</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="info-block">
      <h3>💉 Why Epinephrine — Mechanism of Action</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Receptor</th><th>Effect</th><th>Benefit in Anaphylaxis</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Alpha-1</strong></td><td>Vasoconstriction</td><td>Reverses hypotension; reduces angioedema</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Beta-1</strong></td><td>Increases heart rate and contractility</td><td>Supports cardiac output in shock</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Beta-2</strong></td><td>Bronchodilation</td><td>Reverses bronchoconstriction → improves breathing</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>All receptors</strong></td><td>Inhibits further mediator release from mast cells</td><td>Stops the anaphylactic cascade</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Critical Concept: Epinephrine is FIRST — NOT antihistamines, NOT steroids</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Why epinephrine must come first:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Epinephrine is the only medication that reverses all components of anaphylaxis simultaneously: vasodilation, bronchoconstriction, and mediator release</li>
          <li>Diphenhydramine (Benadryl) blocks histamine receptors but does NOT reverse shock or bronchoconstriction — it cannot save a life in anaphylaxis alone</li>
          <li>Corticosteroids take hours to have effect — they prevent the late biphasic reaction but do nothing for the acute emergency</li>
          <li><strong>Delay in epinephrine = preventable death.</strong> Epinephrine must be given within the first minutes.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Route matters:</strong> IM injection into the <em>lateral thigh</em> (vastus lateralis) provides faster, more reliable absorption than SQ injection. The deltoid is acceptable but lateral thigh is preferred.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ After epinephrine, additional medications are given for ongoing symptom management…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Ongoing Anaphylaxis Management</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Epinephrine has been administered. The provider arrives and gives further orders. Cynthia's vital signs are stabilizing but monitoring is critical.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Adjunct Medications</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Diphenhydramine (Benadryl) 25–50 mg IV</strong> — H1-receptor blocker; reduces urticaria and pruritus; sedation is a side effect; second-line, NOT life-saving</li>
          <li><strong>Methylprednisolone IV</strong> — Corticosteroid; reduces late-phase inflammatory response; prevents biphasic anaphylaxis; takes hours to act</li>
          <li><strong>Albuterol nebulizer</strong> — Short-acting beta-2 agonist; reverses persistent bronchospasm not resolved by epinephrine</li>
          <li><strong>0.9% NS bolus IV</strong> — Fluid resuscitation for distributive hypotension; restores intravascular volume</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Ongoing Monitoring</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Cardiac monitor</th><td>Continuous — watch for dysrhythmias</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td>Every 5 minutes; maintain ≥ 95%</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood pressure</th><td>Every 5 minutes until stable</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory</th><td>Reassess breath sounds after albuterol</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Level of consciousness</th><td>Alert and oriented — assess q15 min</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Critical Concept: Biphasic Anaphylaxis — Why Cynthia Must Be Observed</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Biphasic anaphylaxis:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>In up to 20% of anaphylaxis cases, symptoms return <strong>8 to 72 hours later</strong> without re-exposure to the allergen</li>
          <li>This is the late-phase (biphasic) reaction caused by continued mediator synthesis after the initial mast cell degranulation</li>
          <li>The second reaction can be as severe or MORE severe than the initial one</li>
          <li><strong>Methylprednisolone reduces but does not eliminate biphasic risk</strong></li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Clinical implication:</strong> Cynthia must be observed in-hospital for a minimum of 4–8 hours after anaphylaxis resolution, even when feeling better. Discharge instructions must address signs of returning symptoms.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With the anaphylaxis crisis stabilizing, attention turns to Cynthia's complex medical and personal needs…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Complex Patient Care — ESRD, T1DM, and Inclusive Care</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Cynthia is stable. You now provide holistic, specialized care addressing hemodialysis-related needs, diabetes management, and person-centered inclusive care.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩸 Hemodialysis Access Care</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Check fistula/graft:</strong> Auscultate for bruit (swishing sound), palpate for thrill (vibration) every shift — absence = emergency</li>
          <li><strong>NEVER take blood pressure in the access arm</strong> — compression damages the fistula</li>
          <li><strong>NEVER draw blood from the access arm</strong></li>
          <li><strong>NEVER start IV in the access arm</strong></li>
          <li>Protect access arm from trauma, constrictive clothing, or prolonged pressure</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📉 Post-Dialysis Monitoring</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Hypotension + tachycardia</th><td>Expected after fluid removal during dialysis; monitor for orthostatic hypotension</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood glucose</th><td>Epinephrine raises blood glucose via glycogenolysis; check BG after anaphylaxis treatment</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Electrolytes</th><td>Dialysis alters K⁺, Na⁺, Ca²⁺ — monitor levels post-treatment</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Weight</th><td>Post-dialysis weight documents fluid removal achieved</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-info">
      <strong>🌈 LGBTQ+ Inclusive, Person-Centered Care</strong>
      <p>Cynthia's preferred pronouns should be confirmed and respected throughout all care interactions. Ask at admission: <em>"What pronouns do you use?"</em> and document in the chart. Ask Cynthia who they would like included in care discussions and decisions. Inclusive language and respect for gender identity are components of equitable, person-centered nursing care — not optional additions.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>📋 Incident Report Required</strong>
      <p>A medication error occurred: ampicillin was administered to a patient with a documented penicillin allergy. Complete an incident report per institutional policy. The purpose of incident reporting is <strong>system improvement and patient safety</strong> — not punishment. Document objectively: what happened, when, the patient response, and interventions taken.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Focus: Hemodialysis Vascular Access — Why Protection Matters</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Hemodialysis AV fistula or graft is Cynthia's lifeline:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>The arteriovenous (AV) fistula is a surgical connection between an artery and vein — typically in the forearm or upper arm</li>
          <li>It creates high blood flow required for hemodialysis (blood must be processed 3× per week)</li>
          <li>Loss of access = inability to perform dialysis = risk of uremic crisis and death in ESRD</li>
          <li>Bruit (sound) and thrill (feel) confirm patency — loss of either requires immediate vascular surgery notification</li>
          <li>Compression from BP cuffs, phlebotomy, or IV placement can cause clotting (thrombosis) of the access — an irreversible complication</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your nursing documentation and prioritize diagnoses…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Nursing Diagnoses and SBAR</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Impaired Gas Exchange</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Wheezing, decreased SpO₂, tachypnea secondary to bronchoconstriction from anaphylaxis</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Decreased Cardiac Output</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Hypotension and compensatory tachycardia secondary to distributive shock from anaphylaxis</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Anaphylactic Shock</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Documented penicillin allergy; ampicillin administered; biphasic reaction risk 8–72 hrs post-episode</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Unstable Blood Glucose</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: T1DM; epinephrine administration raises blood glucose via glycogenolysis; ESRD alters insulin clearance</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Medication Error — Actual</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Ampicillin (penicillin class) administered despite documented penicillin allergy; requires incident reporting and provider notification</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Cynthia's Anaphylactic Reaction</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>Calling regarding Cynthia Bennet, 34-year-old African American patient, admitted for UTI with documented penicillin allergy. Cynthia has just experienced an anaphylactic reaction to IV ampicillin inadvertently administered during hemodialysis.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Cynthia has T1DM, ESRD on hemodialysis, and a documented allergy to penicillin. The dialysis unit administered ampicillin IV — a penicillin-class antibiotic — without allergy verification. Cynthia returned to the floor with the infusion running. Symptoms developed within minutes of arrival.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>Symptoms: generalized pruritus → urticaria → wheezing → hypotension and tachycardia. Vital signs deteriorating. Interventions initiated: ampicillin stopped, new IV tubing with NS, call for help, epinephrine 1:1000 0.3 mg IM lateral thigh, O₂ via NRB mask, patient repositioned flat with legs elevated. Vital signs now stabilizing.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: orders for diphenhydramine IV, methylprednisolone IV, albuterol nebulizer, NS bolus; new antibiotic order for UTI (non-penicillin class); continued monitoring orders; incident report initiated. Please come to evaluate.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Epinephrine 1:1000 — 0.3 mg IM</strong> <span class="badge-danger">FIRST-LINE</span></td>
          <td>Sympathomimetic / Vasopressor</td>
          <td>Alpha-1: vasoconstriction reverses hypotension; Beta-2: bronchodilation reverses wheezing; inhibits further mast cell mediator release. Inject into <strong>lateral thigh (vastus lateralis)</strong> — fastest absorption. May repeat every 5–15 minutes. Monitor: HR, BP, SpO₂ after each dose.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Diphenhydramine (Benadryl) 25–50 mg IV</strong></td>
          <td>H1-antihistamine (second-line)</td>
          <td>Blocks H1 histamine receptors — reduces urticaria and pruritus. Does NOT reverse shock or airway compromise. Side effect: significant sedation — implement fall precautions. Administer after epinephrine.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Methylprednisolone (Solu-Medrol) IV</strong></td>
          <td>Corticosteroid</td>
          <td>Reduces late-phase and biphasic anaphylactic response. Takes hours to take effect — not useful for acute emergency. Monitor blood glucose (corticosteroids raise BG — critical for T1DM patient).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Albuterol nebulizer</strong></td>
          <td>Short-acting beta-2 agonist (SABA)</td>
          <td>Reverses persistent bronchospasm. Administer via nebulizer mask. Monitor: heart rate (albuterol causes tachycardia), SpO₂, breath sounds before and after.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>0.9% Normal Saline (NS) bolus</strong></td>
          <td>Isotonic crystalloid IV fluid</td>
          <td>Fluid resuscitation for distributive hypotension — restores intravascular volume lost to vasodilation and third-spacing. Administer as ordered; monitor for fluid overload (critical in ESRD patient with limited renal clearance).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Oxygen — NRB mask</strong></td>
          <td>Supportive therapy</td>
          <td>10–15 L/min via non-rebreather mask for hypoxemia. Goal: SpO₂ ≥ 95%. Advance to bag-valve-mask if SpO₂ does not improve.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What is your first response when Cynthia develops pruritus, erythema, and wheezing?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Stop the ampicillin infusion immediately</strong> — clamp tubing, do NOT remove the IV catheter</li>
          <li>Assess airway, breathing, circulation (ABC)</li>
          <li>Notify the provider and call for help</li>
          <li>Prepare to administer epinephrine IM per order</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: What is the earliest symptom of anaphylaxis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Generalized pruritus (itching)</strong> is typically the earliest symptom of anaphylaxis. It reflects initial histamine release before the full systemic reaction develops. Urticaria (hives) typically follows, then respiratory and cardiovascular symptoms.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What is the priority nursing intervention when anaphylaxis is suspected?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Airway assessment</strong> is always the first priority. Anaphylaxis causes laryngeal edema and bronchoconstriction that can obstruct the airway. Maintaining a patent airway precedes all other interventions.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What is the drug of choice for anaphylaxis, and why not antihistamines?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Epinephrine 1:1000 IM is the drug of choice.</strong> Only epinephrine reverses all three components of anaphylaxis: vasodilation (via alpha-1), bronchoconstriction (via beta-2), and ongoing mediator release. Antihistamines like diphenhydramine block only histamine receptors and cannot reverse hypotension or airway obstruction. Giving antihistamines first delays life-saving epinephrine.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What vital sign pattern indicates anaphylactic shock?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Hypotension with compensatory tachycardia</strong> indicates distributive (anaphylactic) shock. Vasodilation and increased vascular permeability cause massive fluid shift out of the intravascular space → falling blood pressure → reflex tachycardia to maintain cardiac output.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q6: What intervention is indicated when SpO₂ drops during anaphylaxis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Apply high-flow oxygen via non-rebreather (NRB) mask</strong> at 10–15 L/min. The NRB delivers approximately 60–90% FiO₂ to address hypoxemia from bronchoconstriction. If SpO₂ does not improve, prepare for bag-valve-mask ventilation or intubation.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q7: What type of hypersensitivity reaction is anaphylaxis?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Type I — IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.</strong> Previous antigen exposure triggered IgE antibody production and binding to mast cells. Re-exposure causes rapid mast cell degranulation releasing histamine, leukotrienes, and prostaglandins. Onset within seconds to minutes. This is distinct from Type II (cytotoxic), Type III (immune complex), and Type IV (delayed cell-mediated) hypersensitivity.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q8: What post-hemodialysis findings should be anticipated in Cynthia?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Reduced blood pressure and elevated heart rate</strong> are expected after hemodialysis because fluid is removed during the treatment. The nurse should differentiate expected post-dialysis hemodynamic changes from ongoing anaphylactic hypotension, and monitor trends over time with frequent vital signs.</p></div>
    </details>
  </div>

